Add CloudFixity Javascript tests to CI
Run regular local fixity checks via cron

comments.body:
We tried the above solutions. The fastest we could get a 100% index-based DISTINCT and CTE-based solution to work was 11 seconds.

The existing query, at that time, ran in 5 seconds.

EXPLAIN ANALYZE shows that it's pulling something like 1.4 million rows, which is just a lot of rows to unique-ify, which takes time.

@hackartisan and I discussed an alternate strategy:

1. Add a `current: true/false` property to Event.
2. When adding a new event that has the same type, resource_id, and child_id, mark the previously current event with that type, resource_id, and child_id as `current: false`.
3. In this query, just select where current: true. That should use an index and be very fast.

These are the things we tried, some of which may be useful for a migration as part of the above:

CTE + ROW_NUMBER (could be adjusted to find everything that's not the first row)
```sql
WITH summary AS (
  select res.*, ROW_NUMBER() OVER(PARTITION BY res.metadata->>'child_id' ORDER BY res.updated_at DESC) AS rank FROM orm_resources res WHERE res.internal_resource = 'Event'
) select * from summary WHERE rank = 1 AND metadata @> '{"status": ["FAILURE"]}' ORDER BY updated_at ASC LIMIT 50;
```

SELECT DISTINCT
```sql
WITH summary AS (
  SELECT DISTINCT ON (metadata->>'child_id') * FROM orm_resources WHERE internal_resource = 'Event' ORDER BY metadata->>'child_id', updated_at DESC LIMIT 50
) select * from summary WHERE metadata @> '{"status": ["FAILURE"]}' ORDER BY updated_at ASC LIMIT 50;
```


Indexes we built to speed up SELECT DISTINCT and CTE/ROW_NUMBER

```sql
CREATE INDEX event_metadata_child_id_idx ON orm_resources ((metadata->>'child_id'), updated_at DESC) WHERE (internal_resource) = 'Event'
```

Existing query, but minus a few checks (resource_id and child_property):
```sql
SELECT res.* FROM orm_resources AS res WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT a.* FROM orm_resources AS a WHERE
  a.internal_resource = res.internal_resource AND
  a.metadata @> '{"status": ["SUCCESS"]}' AND
  a.metadata->'child_id' = res.metadata->'child_id' AND
  a.updated_at >= res.updated_at
) AND
res.metadata @> '{"status": ["FAILURE"]}' AND
res.internal_resource = 'Event'
ORDER BY res.updated_at ASC
LIMIT 50
```

Removing those extra checks cut off like a second, not significant enough to do.
Close in favor of #5589

pdc_describe.title: Add note in storage.yml to explain development against AWS
Mechanism for free-text notes in provenance log
Develop a statement for our provenance log which describes our migration process

comments.body:
Bess points out that this can't just be a comment on the record: We need to be sure it's in the provenance so it will be persisted... And there's no provision right now for free text in the provenance log. I'll file a new issue for that: This issue is just to come up with text and apply it to the records.

- Update: filed #720

@bess This longer statement belongs in the repository documentation, not the provenance log. A shorter statement to indicate the record was migrated and re-described can be placed in the provenance log. Tyler's (or whomever else) performs the change to the record should be recorded to the provenance log in the same way it will record changes made by other users. (note: I'm not totally happy with how the provenance log is capturing contributors to the record, so we can talk more about versions of names recorded.)

### Example of what I would like to see in the provenance log:
 
![Screen Shot 2022-12-13 at 10 16 58 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/50670293/207372227-38da62ee-3d9c-442f-9fc2-a0b1c1b3d899.jpeg)


### Example from the current provenance log in Describe:
![Screen Shot 2022-12-13 at 9 53 32 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/50670293/207366825-881cc794-2ece-4039-9545-a4699681ed51.jpeg)


### Example from ScholarSphere (see migration info):
![Screen Shot 2022-12-13 at 9 47 49 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/50670293/207365858-61206426-f6cc-4b55-ab3f-8eb84e332aa9.jpeg)

@bess @mccalluc We need to talk about what goes in this log and what should be in separate documentation. Lengthy statements will clutter the log. The "why" does not need to be described in each record if we know this was originally in DataSpace, Translated by [name] to Datacite, and migrated. Further details (or lengthy statements) belong in separate documentation that can be referred to if someone inquires about the migration process.

I'm happy with the three shorter statements in the provenance log for the object. Seems to me that meets the CTS requirements, and if keeping the log short and easily scanned is a goal this seems like a good way to do that. 

@mccalluc Thanks for pointing out the need to record user-entered statements into the provenance log, and thank you for writing that ticket.

@bess I like this statement though and want to see it in our documentation for the repository. It belongs with further detailed description of the migration, rather than in the provenance log. 

We do want to keep the provenance log shorter for curators and other users to quickly be able to scan and find what may be needed.

Per conversation with @astrochun and @hhkitsune, this is not a priority for MVP.  ROR is not widely known or supported for PPPL constituents, and DOE does not currently support ROR for funding information reports. 

We are interested in supporting this feature in the future (alongside free text options), but this is not a high priority right now.

Note, the non-ROR part of this ticket is still a priority for the migration.
